00:13:58,134 --> 00:14:00,956
When the game's finished, is it going to be sellable?

126
00:14:01,176 --> 00:14:02,316
Is it going to be explainable?

127
00:14:02,697 --> 00:14:04,157
Is this something I can market?

128
00:14:04,418 --> 00:14:06,519
The whole kind of concept gets tied up here.

129
00:14:07,319 --> 00:14:11,682
So the method is to come up with a theme.

130
00:14:12,222 --> 00:14:15,604
So the theme is, what is the question that we're exploring here?

131
00:14:15,624 --> 00:14:18,005
And it might be a question I don't have an answer to.

132
00:14:19,938 --> 00:14:19,998
and

133
00:14:37,728 --> 00:14:38,748
And then there's the emotion.

134
00:14:39,569 --> 00:14:49,493
And this is kind of key to me, is as a storyteller, I want to have a really specific emotion that I felt that I want to communicate.

135
00:14:50,474 --> 00:14:55,516
And to communicate that needs an experience, right?

136
00:14:55,576 --> 00:14:59,118
If I was to just put it into words, it would sound trite or unspecific.

137
00:14:59,658 --> 00:15:05,441
So how do we create an experience, and through living that experience, have the player

138
00:15:06,638 --> 00:15:07,499
feel this emotion.

139
00:15:07,799 --> 00:15:16,967
So for example in Telling Lies the emotion was how does it feel to have been in a relationship that's failed

140
00:15:18,154 --> 00:15:23,578
but still hold in your head the memories of the happy memories of when that relationship was working, right?

141
00:15:23,598 --> 00:15:31,803
And it's a very complicated part of being a human is holding these conflicting emotions and still having the spark and the way that memory works.

142
00:15:32,724 --> 00:15:35,626
Like there was this real gnarly little emotion there.

143
00:15:35,646 --> 00:15:40,089
It was like, how do we get people to experience that and think about it?

144
00:15:40,269 --> 00:15:42,951
Because if I express it like I just did, it's kind of lame.

145
00:15:43,993 --> 00:15:46,197
And then a key thing is the metaphor.

146
00:15:46,477 --> 00:15:49,522
I call it, I'm slightly breaking the use of the word metaphor.

147
00:15:50,183 --> 00:15:51,065
The idea here is

148
00:15:52,185 --> 00:16:15,932
what is what is the metaphor and kind of it becomes the mechanic that describes the game and this becomes really useful communication tool to the player so for example with her story the metaphor was that moment in a police show where the detective is sat at the computer and they've run out of leads they're at the you know it's

